natives. I show that, defined one way, the uncovered set is equal to the set of Pareto allocations that give over half the voters a strictly positive payoff, while alternate definitions yield an uncovered set that is equal to the entire Pareto set. These results highlight a small error in Epstein (1998) in which the author characterizes the uncovered set for a different definition of covering than claimed.";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_url";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_doi";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_issue";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";s:0:"";s:23:"biblio_accession_number";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_call_number";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_notes";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_coins";s:374:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fscholar.iq.harvard.edu&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Alternate+definitions+of+the+uncovered+set%2C+and+their+implications&amp;rft.title=Social+Choice+and+Welfare&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.aulast=Penn&amp;rft.aufirst=Elizabeth+Maggie"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom1";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom2";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom3";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom4";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom5";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom6";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom7";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_auth_address";s:0:"";s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";s:0:"";s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:"129";s:12:"biblio_label";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_access_date";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:15:"Journal Article";s:4:"path";s:64:"epenn/alternate-definitions-uncovered-set-and-their-implications";s:9:"og_groups";a:1:{i:0;i:113;}s:14:"og_groups_both";a:1:{i:113;s:5:"epenn";}s:9:"og_public";b:1;s:4:"tags";a:1:{i:6;a:2:{i:60;O:8:"stdClass":5:{s:3:"tid";s:2:"60";s:3:"vid";s:1:"6";s:4:"name";s:21:"Alternate definitions";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"weight";s:1:"0";}i:51;O:8:"stdClass":5:{s:3:"tid";s:2:"51";s:3