ions will improve the planning of future studies, reduce necessary sample size (and cost), and allow the analyst to extract additional information from the list experiment. In particular, the conditional list experiment estimator (introduced in this paper), estimates the probability that an individual holds a socially undesirable belief/trait/behavior, conditional on their response to the corresponding indirect question. This technique can be used to improve population estimates, to impute individual respondent answers, and in combination with directly-asked sensitive questions, can be used to estimate the probability that a respondent is lying.";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";s:74:"list experiment: item count technique; indirect questioning; survey design";s:10:"biblio_url";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_doi";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_issue";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";s:0:"";s:23:"biblio_accession_number";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_call_number";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_notes";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_coins";s:428:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Adc&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fscholar.iq.harvard.edu&amp;rft.title=On+the+Design+of+Statistical+Truth+Serum%3A+Getting+More+from+the+List+Experiment+with+Sample+Size+Calculation%2C+Design+Principles%2C+and+the+Probabilistic+Imputation+of+Socially+Undesirable+Responses&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.aulast=Glynn&amp;rft.aufirst=Adam"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom1";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom2";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom3";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom4";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom5";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom6";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom7";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_auth_address";s:0:"";s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";s:0:"";s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:"225";s:12:"biblio_label";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_access_date";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:13:"Working Paper";s:4:"path";s:100:"aglynn/on-