(491, 'scholar_class', 'O:8:"stdClass":33:{s:3:"nid";s:3:"491";s:3:"vid";s:3:"491";s:4:"type";s:13:"scholar_class";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:7:"created";s:10:"1240852927";s:7:"changed";s:10:"1240852927";s:7:"comment";s:1:"0";s:7:"promote";s:1:"0";s:6:"sticky";s:1:"0";s:18:"revision_timestamp";s:10:"1240852927";s:5:"title";s:47:"Historical Study A-51: The Modern World Economy";s:4:"body";s:893:"Historical Study A-51 : The Modern World Economy, 1873-2000\r\nHarvard College/GSAS: 1263\r\nFall 2008-2009\r\nJeffry Frieden\r\nLocation: CGIS-South S-020 Case Study Room\r\nMeeting Time: M., W., 2-3:30, and a 90-minute weekly section to be arranged.\r\nExam Group: 7,8\r\nThe past 125 years have seen more rapid economic growth, and more global economic integration, than ever before. Yet the gap between rich and poor countries has widened, and "globalization" has alternated with attempts at national self-sufficiency under fascist, communist, and other banners. The course explores the impact of technological, economic, social, and political trends, at both global and national levels, on the development of the world economy since 1873. Topics include free trade and the gold standard in the 19th century, European colonialism, the depressions of 1873-96 and 1929-39, and the postwar economic order. ";s:6:"teaser";s:259:"Historical Study A-51 : The Modern World Economy, 1873-2000\r\nHarvard College/GSAS: 1263\r\nFall 2008-2009\r\nJeffry Frieden\r\nLocation: CGIS-South S-020 Case Study Room\r\nMeeting Time: M., W., 2-3:30, and a 90-minute weekly section to be arranged.\r\nExam Group: 7,8\r";s:3:"log";s:0:"";s:6:"format";s:1:"1";s:3:"uid";s:2:"24";s:4:"name";s:8:"jfrieden";s:7:"picture";s:0:"";s:4:"data";s:98:"a:3:{s:6:"submit";s:18:"Create new account";s:7:"form_id";s:13:"user_register";s:7:"contact";i:1;}";s:4:"path";s:55:"jfrieden/historical-study-a-51-the-modern-world-economy";s:9:"og_groups";a:1:{i:0;i:327;}s:14:"og_groups_both";a:1:{i:327;s:8:"jfrieden";}s:9:"og_public";b:1;s:4:"ta