(551, 'scholar_class', 'O:8:"stdClass":33:{s:3:"nid";s:3:"551";s:3:"vid";s:3:"551";s:4:"type";s:13:"scholar_class";s:6:"status";s:1:"1";s:7:"created";s:10:"1247592205";s:7:"changed";s:10:"1247767240";s:7:"comment";s:1:"0";s:7:"promote";s:1:"0";s:6:"sticky";s:1:"0";s:18:"revision_timestamp";s:10:"1247767240";s:5:"title";s:40:"GOV 98gs Globalization and Civil Society";s:4:"body";s:1260:"This seminar explores the concept of civil society, looking at Western Europe and the US and then at Asia. We first explore the origins of the notion of civil society in Western thought and history, examining the debates over it and over related concepts such as the public sphere, social capital and civic engagement.  We look at the relation between civil society and democracy, both in established democracies and in countries before, during, and after democratic transitions.  We then look at country cases, including Japan, South Korea, Taiwan, and China, but the seminar also draws on examples from a number of other countries in Asia, including India, Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Mongolia, and Vietnam. A key question is how civil societies ever arise in the first place; hence, we look at what forms civil society takes under conditions of severe repression or ethnic strife. Among the issues and problems we take up are: the relation between the state and civil society; the role of civil society in political change; the role of religious groups as civil society actors; the rise of transborder NGOs; and the emergence of international civil society and Asia’s place in it.\r\n\r\n(In the past this course was called GOV 90gs.)";s:6:"teaser";s:479:"This seminar explores the concept of civil society, looking at Western Europe and the US and then at Asia. We first explore the origins of the notion of civil society in Western thought and history, examining the debates over it and over related concepts such as the public sphere, social capital and civic engagement.  We look 