for the outcome variable. After\r\n  explaining the AIPW estimator, we conduct a Monte Carlo experiment\r\n  that compares the performance of the AIPW estimator to three common\r\n  competitors: a regression estimator, an inverse propensity weighted\r\n  (IPW) estimator, and a propensity score matching estimator. The\r\n  Monte Carlo results show that the AIPW estimator is dramatically\r\n  superior to the other estimators in many situations and at least as\r\n  good as the other estimators across a wide range of data generating\r\n  processes.\r\n";s:13:"biblio_abst_f";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_full_text";s:1:"0";s:15:"biblio_keywords";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_url";s:0:"";s:10:"biblio_doi";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_issue";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_type_of_work";s:0:"";s:23:"biblio_accession_number";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_call_number";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_notes";s:0:"";s:12:"biblio_coins";s:420:"<span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Adc&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fscholar.iq.harvard.edu&amp;rft.title=Robust+and+Efficient+Estimation+of+Average+Treatment+Effects+in+++Cross-Sectional+Studies%3A+An+Introduction+to+the+Augmented+Inverse+++Propensity+Weighted+Estimator++&amp;rft.date=2009&amp;rft.aulast=Glynn&amp;rft.aufirst=Adam&amp;rft.au=Quinn%2C+Kevin"></span>";s:21:"biblio_research_notes";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom1";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom2";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom3";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom4";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom5";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom6";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_custom7";s:0:"";s:19:"biblio_auth_address";s:0:"";s:21:"biblio_remote_db_name";s:0:"";s:25:"biblio_remote_db_provider";s:0:"";s:14:"biblio_citekey";s:3:"645";s:12:"biblio_label";s:0:"";s:18:"biblio_access_date";s:0:"";s:16:"biblio_type_name";s:13:"Working Paper";s:4:"path";s:100:"aglynn/robust-and-efficient-estimation-average-treatment-effects-cross-sectional-studies-an-introduc";s:9:"og_groups";a:1:{i:0;i:31;}s:14:"og_groups_both";a:1:{i:31;s:6:"aglynn";}s:9:"og_publi